DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain addresses the ethics of citation practices through the lens of epistemic injustice. Miranda Fricker's 2007 foundational work identified testimonial and hermeneutical injustice as distinctively epistemic wrongs that harm people in their capacity as knowers. Testimonial injustice occurs when prejudice causes a speaker to receive deflated credibility; hermeneutical injustice arises when marginalized groups lack collective conceptual resources to articulate their experiences. This framework has been extensively applied and critiqued, with Kristie Dotson expanding it to include contributory injustice (when marginalized knowers are prevented from contributing to collective hermeneutical resources) and epistemic violence (systematic silencing). Jos\u00e9 Medina's work develops the notion of epistemic resistance and the collective dimensions of epistemic oppression.

The domain specifically addresses how citational practices perpetuate or resist these injustices. Citation functions as a form of testimonial recognition: who gets cited, whose work is rendered invisible, and whose perspectives are marginalized in scholarly knowledge production all reflect and reinforce broader patterns of epistemic injustice. Recent work explores citational justice as a subspecies of testimonial justice, examining how gender, race, geography, and institutional prestige shape citation networks in philosophy. Empirical studies document systematic citation bias, while normative work debates scholars' ethical obligations in citation practices and whether social justice considerations should influence bibliographic selection.

Key debates include: whether citational justice demands demographic representation or substantive engagement with marginalized perspectives; whether "strategic" citation for social justice reasons constitutes ethically bad epistemic practice; how to balance epistemic and ethical considerations in citation; and whether literature reviews themselves can instantiate epistemic injustice through exclusionary citational practices.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is central to the metaphilosophical inquiry into literature review methodology and ethics. Literature reviews are constituted through citational choices—every bibliography embodies decisions about whose testimony to include, amplify, or omit. The epistemic injustice framework illuminates how ostensibly neutral methodological practices (comprehensiveness, relevance criteria, quality standards) can systematically exclude marginalized voices while claiming objectivity. The domain provides conceptual tools to analyze whether and how literature reviews perpetuate testimonial and hermeneutical injustice, and what citational justice would require of reviewers.

