  RELEVANCE: This paper directly addresses the politics and ethics of what counts as "the philosophical literature" in an era of globalization. It argues that current approaches to diversity in philosophy fail because they operate within Western metaphilosophical assumptions about what philosophy is. For a project on literature reviews in philosophy, Denecke's analysis implies that the very question "what is the relevant literature?" cannot be answered without confronting the hegemony of Western philosophical canons and methods. Her call for metaphilosophical reflection as a prerequisite for genuine globalization suggests that literature review methodologies must themselves be reconceived to recognize diverse philosophical traditions.

  POSITION: Critical global philosophy, arguing for metaphilosophical reconstruction to enable genuine philosophical pluralism.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, global-philosophy, decolonial, High},
  abstract = {This essay attempts to understand the forces behind the current deadlock over globalizing academic philosophy between main-stream Western-style philosophers and its currently marginalized diversity advocates. It first pinpoints what Western-style philosophers might consider threatening or simply uninteresting in some of the major diversity paradigms (“The Same,” “The Subaltern,” “The Samaritan,” and “The Area Studies Silo”). Second, it introduces a secret weapon nobody seems to have put to use yet: metaphilosophy. It argues that we need to take a deeper historical and philological breath to redraw what and where “philosophy” has thrived in world history. Only through the detour of a global, deep-time metaphilosophy can we bring the most ingenious human thought and philosophical practice to the table as we battle over a more cosmopolitan future for academic philosophy and try to forge philosophical tools to tackle the global challenges in our world of interlocking social, spiritual, and environmental crises.},
