  RELEVANCE: This article addresses the methodology of metaphilosophy itself, providing a framework for thinking about methodological debates. For literature review methodology, it suggests that prescriptive methodologies for conducting reviews cannot be developed independently of examining how philosophical literature reviews actually function in practice. At the same time, descriptive accounts of existing review practices do not automatically vindicate those practices. This implies that developing a methodology for philosophical literature reviews requires both empirical investigation of actual practices and normative reflection on their justification.

  POSITION: Meta-metaphilosophical, arguing for integration of descriptive and normative approaches in philosophical methodology.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, methodology, experimental-philosophy, Medium},
  abstract = {Experimental philosophy, at least in its ‘negative’ variety, has standardly been portrayed as presenting a dramatic challenge to traditional philosophical methodology. As such, it has prompted a large variety of counter-arguments and defenses of intuition. In this paper, I argue that many of these objections to experimental philosophy rest on various oversimplifications that both experimental philosophers and their opponents have made regarding intuitions and philosophical methodology. Once these oversimplifications are abandoned, I argue that the experimentalist critique of current philosophical methods becomes somewhat less dramatic, but also much less open to objection.postprin},
  abstract_source = {core},
}

@book{Schmid2022methods,
  author = {Schmid, Jelscha},
  title = {The Methods of Metaphilosophy: Kant, Maimon, and Schelling on How to Philosophize about Philosophy},
  year = {2022},
  doi = {10.5771/9783465145981},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Schmid examines how Kant, Salomon Maimon, and F.W.J. Schelling developed distinctive methods for philosophizing about philosophy itself. The book argues that these German Idealist philosophers recognized that metaphilosophy requires distinctive methods because of its special object: philosophy itself. The investigation proceeds by examining how these thinkers engaged with 18th-century scientific theories and practices, showing that philosophical experiments, fictions, and models offer methodological solutions to the problem of developing a scientific metaphysics. The book demonstrates that metaphilosophical reflection has a sophisticated methodological history.

  RELEVANCE: This historical study shows that the problem of how to conduct metaphilosophical inquiry (including inquiry into philosophical methods) has a rich intellectual tradition. For literature review methodology, it suggests that reflecting on how to review philosophical literature is itself a metaphilosophical question requiring appropriate methods. The emphasis on how German Idealists drew on scientific practices of their era to develop philosophical methods suggests that contemporary literature review methodologies might similarly benefit from engaging with current scholarly practices in adjacent fields while maintaining awareness of philosophy's distinctive character.

  POSITION: Historical metaphilosophy examining the development of methods for second-order philosophical inquiry.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, methods, German-idealism, Medium},
  abstract = {On the basis of an examination of Kant's, Maimon's and Schelling's metaphilosophies, this book investigates how, starting from Kant's diagnosis of a "groping metaphysics", a philosophical research program, whose goal is to elucidate the nature and method of philosophy itself, develops. What unites their projects is the thesis that philosophy must begin with an investigation of its own nature, and that this investigation, because of its special object, must be accompanied by a reflection on its method. To this end, their methods are discussed on the assumption that these methods arise from a particular engagement with the theories and practices of the 18th century sciences. Finally, this discussion provides the basis for showing in what ways philosophical experiments, fictions, or models offer methodological solutions to the problem of developing a scientific metaphysics.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{Reinoso2022neopyrrhonism,
  author = {Reinoso, Guadalupe},
  title = {Neopyrrhonism as Metaphilosophy: A Non-Quietist Proposal},
  journal = {Praxis Filos\'ofica},
  year = {2022},
  doi = {10.25100/pfilosofica.v0i54.11935},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Reinoso argues against the interpretation of Neopyrrhonism (linking Wittgenstein and ancient Pyrrhonian skepticism) as a quietist metaphilosophy that cancels philosophy through self-destructive arguments. Instead, she proposes interpreting Neopyrrhonism as a performative metaphilosophy that is an open-ended inquiry using different philosophical argumentative strategies to encourage new ways of practicing philosophy. This non-quietist Neopyrrhonism involves skepticism about philosophy based on philosophical arguments, but does not conclude that philosophy should cease; rather, it transforms how philosophy is done.

  RELEVANCE: This article offers an alternative metaphilosophical position that is skeptical about traditional philosophical methods while remaining engaged in philosophical inquiry. For literature review methodology, a Neopyrrhonist approach would emphasize examining the arguments and presuppositions in the literature rather than accepting them, using the literature performatively to generate new philosophical questions. This contrasts with approaches that treat the literature as a body of established results to build upon. The distinction between quietist and non-quietist metaphilosophy also maps onto different possible attitudes toward philosophical literature: accepting its authority vs. subjecting it to ongoing critical scrutiny.

  POSITION: Skeptical but non-quietist metaphilosophy emphasizing performative and critical engagement with philosophy.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, skepticism, Wittgenstein, Medium},
  abstract = {Fogelin (2002 [1976]; 1992 [1981]; 1994) was the first one to speak about “Neopyrrhonism” to link Wittgenstein and Sextus Empiricus. To him, Pyrrhonism “combines philosophical scepticism with scepticism about philosophy, that is, to have doubts about philosophy on the basis of philosophical arguments” (1994, p. 3). Following this interpretation, Neopyrrhonism can be understood as a kind of scepticism that cancels philosophy using self-destructive arguments (peritrope). Both Sextus -with his proposal of suspension of judgment- and Wittgenstein -with his idea of the dissolution of philosophical problems- are representatives of quietism. Neopyrrhonism as quietism can be conceived of as a therapeutic proposal mainly based on not postulating an argumentative-constructive philosophical theory. Against this perspective, I propose interpreting Neopyrrhonism as Metaphilosophy, from which a performative proposal emerges. In this approach, Neopyrrhonism is an open-ended inquiry that implies the ability of using different philosophical argumentative strategies in a performative sense to encourage a new way of exercising philosophy. },
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{Yetman2025metaphor,
  author = {Yetman, Cameron C.},
  title = {Metaphor and Metaphilosophy: Wittgenstein, MacDonald, and Conceptual Metaphor Theory},
  journal = {European Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2025},
  doi = {10.1111/ejop.13038},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Yetman argues that Conceptual Metaphor Theory's (CMT) critique of philosophy—that philosophical concepts and arguments rely on unacknowledged metaphorical structures that can lead philosophy astray—was anticipated by Wittgenstein and his student Margaret MacDonald. Wittgenstein's method of identifying and resolving philosophical puzzles generated by misused grammatical analogies, and MacDonald's analysis of how and why such analogies create problems, both prefigure CMT's claims about metaphor in philosophy. Yetman supplements these historical figures' diagnoses with evidence from CMT showing that linguistic metaphors often originate in deeper cognitive mappings.

  RELEVANCE: This article addresses how metaphors and analogies function in philosophical reasoning, with implications for how we read philosophical literature. If philosophical arguments often rely on implicit metaphorical structures, then understanding a piece of philosophical literature requires identifying these structures. For literature review methodology, this suggests that reviews should attend not just to explicit arguments but to the metaphors and analogies that structure philosophical discourse. It also implies that different philosophical traditions may employ different root metaphors, making cross-traditional literature reviews particularly challenging.

  POSITION: Critical metaphilosophy examining the role of metaphor and analogy in philosophical method and argumentation.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, metaphor, Wittgenstein, methodology, Low},
  abstract = {The discipline of philosophy has been critiqued from both within and outside itself. One brand of external critique is associated with Conceptual Metaphor Theory (CMT), the view that human cognition is partially structured by pervasive and automatic mappings between conceptual domains. Most notably, Lakoff and Johnson (1999) claimed that many central philosophical concepts and arguments rely on an unacknowledged metaphorical substructure, and that this structure has sometimes led philosophy astray. The purpose of this paper is to argue that Lakoff and Johnson's critique is anticipated by the work of post‐Tractarian Wittgenstein and his student, Margaret MacDonald. In the Blue Book, Wittgenstein outlines a method for identifying and resolving philosophical puzzles generated by misused grammatical analogies, although his discussion lacks a precise characterization of exactly how and why such analogies lead to trouble. In a 1938 paper, MacDonald offers such a characterization, which I outline and then connect back to Wittgenstein. In addition to this interpretive work, I supplement Wittgenstein and MacDonald's diagnosis using evidence from CMT which suggests that linguistic metaphors and analogies often originate in or are motivated by more fundamental analogical mappings in cognition. The supplemented account carries implications for how philosophical arguments ought to be formulated and critiqued.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{Pati2025hegel,
  author = {Pati, Mario},
  title = {Hegel's Metaphilosophy and Its Relevance for Contemporary Philosophy},
  journal = {History of Philosophy \& Logical Analysis},
  year = {2025},
  doi = {10.30965/26664275-bja10110},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Pati examines what it means to speak of a "Hegelian metaphilosophy" and assesses Hegel's relevance for contemporary metaphilosophical debates. He argues that Hegel developed a distinctive conception of philosophy as the self-conscious comprehension of its own historical development, where philosophy is both historically situated and capable of grasping its own historicity. This Hegelian metaphilosophy offers resources for contemporary debates about philosophical progress, the relationship between philosophy and its history, and the possibility of overcoming philosophical disagreements through dialectical development.

  RELEVANCE: Hegel's metaphilosophy offers a distinctive account of how philosophical inquiry relates to its own history—neither treating the history of philosophy as mere preparatory material (as in cumulative progress models) nor as historically relative with no trans-historical standards (as in radical historicism). For literature review methodology, a Hegelian approach would emphasize understanding how current philosophical questions emerge from the internal development of past philosophical positions, requiring literature reviews to reconstruct this dialectical development rather than simply cataloging positions. This contrasts with both naturalistic and purely historical approaches.

  POSITION: Hegelian-historicist metaphilosophy emphasizing philosophy's self-conscious relation to its own history.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, Hegel, history-of-philosophy, Low},
  abstract = {
  abstract_source = {s2},
In recent years, many studies on the relationship between G. W. F. Hegel and metaphilosophy have appeared, articulating it in various ways. The goal of this paper is to specify in what sense it is possible to speak of a Hegelian metaphilosophy, while also assessing the relevance of Hegel for the current metaphilosophical debate. In particular, I will proceed as follows. First, I will outline the main features of the contemporary metaphilosophical debate. Second, I will discuss some important metaphilosophical interpretations of Hegel. Third, I will specify in what sense it is possible to speak of a Hegelian metaphilosophy. Fourth, I will address several methodological issues that arise whenever one attempts to assert the contemporary relevance of Hegel’s philosophy. Finally, I will assess to what extent Hegel’s philosophy can be relevant for the current metaphilosophical debate. As a result, the present paper outlines a concrete option for current philosophical research.},
}

@article{Utomo2025hegemony,
