  RELEVANCE: Rare paper explicitly connecting citation practices to epistemic justice framework. Provides empirical demonstration of how citational patterns in journals constitute epistemic injustice. The systematic review methodology offers model for analyzing citational justice/injustice. Directly relevant to literature review ethics by showing citational choices as sites of potential injustice. The six-part epistemic justice framework could be applied to evaluate literature review practices.

