  that the duty is exceptionless in scholarship raises the question: does failing
  to engage with relevant literature constitute deception by omission? This provides
  a strong normative framework for literature review ethics.

  POSITION: Deontological/virtue-theoretic account of intellectual honesty as
  exceptionless duty in scholarship; focuses on preventing deception rather than
  promoting positive epistemic goods.
  },
  keywords = {intellectual-honesty, research-ethics, deception, Kantian-ethics, High, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

@article{miller2022intellectual,
  author = {Miller, Christian B.},
  title = {Intellectual Honesty},
  journal = {Scientia et Fides},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {10},
  number = {2},
  pages = {83--98},
  doi = {10.12775/setf.2022.021},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Miller offers a preliminary account of intellectual honesty focused
  on its behavioral and motivational dimensions. The intellectually honest person
  reliably does not intentionally distort the facts as she takes them to be,
  motivated by intellectually virtuous reasons (truth-seeking, intellectual
  excellence, respect for others as epistemic agents). Miller distinguishes
  intellectual honesty from moral honesty and emphasizes that it involves both
  behavioral patterns (not distorting facts) and characteristic motivations (valuing
  truth and understanding).

  RELEVANCE: Provides a more recent and accessible account of intellectual honesty
  than Guenin, focusing on virtue rather than duty. Miller's emphasis on not
  intentionally distorting facts raises questions about how selective literature
  engagement relates to distortion—does omitting relevant work distort the
  scholarly record? His focus on motivation is important for understanding whether
  literature review practices reflect genuine commitment to truth or are driven by
  other motives (efficiency, confirmation bias, competitive advantage).

  POSITION: Virtue-theoretic account emphasizing behavioral dispositions and
  intellectually virtuous motivations; focuses on avoiding intentional distortion of
  facts.
  },
  keywords = {intellectual-honesty, virtue-epistemology, truth, High},
  abstract = {Until recently, almost nothing had been written about the moral virtue of honesty in the past 50 years of Western analytic philosophy. Slowly, this is beginning to change. But moral honesty is not the only kind of honesty there is. In this paper, I focus specifically on the intellectual cousin to moral honesty, and offer a preliminary account of its behavioral and motivational dimensions. The account will be centered on not intentionally distorting the facts as the person takes them to be, for one of a variety of intellectually virtuous motivating reasons.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{byerly2022intellectual,
  author = {Byerly, T. Ryan},
  title = {Intellectual Honesty and Intellectual Transparency},
  journal = {Episteme},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {20},
  number = {2},
  pages = {410--428},
  doi = {10.1017/epi.2021.54},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Byerly examines the relationship between intellectual honesty (as
  developed by Nathan King adapting Christian Miller's work) and intellectual
  transparency (Byerly's own account). Intellectual transparency involves openly
  sharing one's intellectual states, processes, and limitations with others in ways
  that facilitate mutual understanding and epistemic cooperation. Byerly argues that
  intellectual transparency can be understood either as an exceptionally strong
  variety of intellectual honesty or as a distinct but related cardinal virtue.
  Transparency goes beyond honesty by requiring positive disclosure rather than
  merely avoiding deception.

  RELEVANCE: The distinction between honesty and transparency is crucial for
  literature review ethics. While intellectual honesty might only prohibit
  misrepresenting what one has read, intellectual transparency would require
  disclosing what one has not read or what limitations exist in one's literature
  coverage. Byerly's account suggests that responsible scholarship may require not
  just avoiding deception but actively revealing gaps and limitations in one's
  knowledge. This has direct implications for how scholars should acknowledge the
  scope and boundaries of their literature reviews.

  POSITION: Virtue-theoretic account distinguishing intellectual honesty (avoiding
  deception) from intellectual transparency (positive disclosure); suggests
  transparency may be a more demanding virtue.
  },
  keywords = {intellectual-honesty, intellectual-transparency, virtue-epistemology, disclosure, High},
  abstract = {Abstract The purpose of this paper is to advance understanding of intellectually virtuous honesty, by examining the relationship between a recent account of intellectual honesty and a recent account of intellectual transparency. The account of intellectual honesty comes from Nathan King, who adapts the work of Christian Miller on moral honesty, while the account of intellectual transparency comes from T. Ryan Byerly. After introducing the respective accounts, I identify four potential differences between intellectual honesty and intellectual transparency as understood by these accounts. I then turn to the question of how to think about the relationship between these traits in light of these potential differences. I make the case that intellectual transparency can either be regarded as an exceptionally strong or ideal variety of intellectual honesty, or it can be regarded as a distinct virtue from intellectual honesty which is a more cardinal virtue than the latter. Along the way, I also note some places where a case can be made that Miller's and King's accounts of honesty and intellectual honesty are in need of refinement or clarification.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{king2014perseverance,
  author = {King, Nathan L.},
  title = {Perseverance as an intellectual virtue},
  journal = {Synthese},
  year = 2014,
  volume = {191},
  number = {15},
  pages = {3501--3523},
  doi = {10.1007/s11229-014-0418-1},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: King develops an account of intellectual perseverance as a virtue,
  distinct from but related to other intellectual virtues like conscientiousness,
  honesty, courage, and open-mindedness. Intellectual perseverance involves
  sustained engagement with difficult intellectual tasks despite obstacles,
  setbacks, and temptations to give up. King argues that intellectual perseverance
  is valuable both instrumentally (it helps achieve truth) and constitutively (it
  reflects proper valuation of intellectual goods).

  RELEVANCE: While not directly about honesty or integrity, King's analysis of
  intellectual perseverance connects to literature review ethics in important ways.
  Comprehensive literature engagement requires perseverance—the willingness to
  continue searching, reading, and synthesizing even when it becomes tedious or
  overwhelming. King's work suggests that virtuous scholarship involves not just
  avoiding dishonesty but also cultivating the stamina to pursue thorough
  understanding. This virtue-theoretic framework complements duty-based accounts by
  highlighting the dispositional qualities that enable responsible scholarship.

  POSITION: Virtue-theoretic account of intellectual perseverance as essential for
  sustained inquiry; complements other intellectual virtues in enabling good
  scholarship.
  },
  keywords = {intellectual-virtue, perseverance, virtue-epistemology, Medium, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

@article{baehr2013educating,
  author = {Baehr, Jason},
  title = {Educating for Intellectual Virtues: From Theory to Practice},
  journal = {Journal of Philosophy of Education},
  year = {2013},
  volume = {47},
  number = {2},
  pages = {248--262},
  doi = {10.1111/1467-9752.12023},
  note = {
