  open-mindedness, intellectual courage, intellectual honesty, and attentiveness)
  should be central aims of education. He distinguishes reliabilist conceptions of
  intellectual virtue (stable cognitive faculties) from responsibilist conceptions
  (character traits like the ones listed). Baehr advocates for the responsibilist
  approach and outlines how intellectual virtue education can be implemented in
  practice through modeling, direct instruction, and creating supportive
  institutional cultures.

  RELEVANCE: Baehr's work on intellectual virtue education provides a framework for
  understanding how scholarly norms and practices are transmitted through training
  and pedagogy. If intellectual virtues are cultivated through education and
